node.text:
We have a collective moral mission, to reaffirm how we live in remembrance. 

Let us strive to show the same courage in our compassion; strength in our empathy; grit in generosity and invincibility in our love for one another as those did on that day, who died, who responded, who stood up when they tried to knock our nation down. 

Today is about reflection and ceremony... and it must also be about how we, the living, dedicate our lives.

node.text: Millions of American families are about to receive up to $3,600 per child thanks to the expanded child tax credit in the American Rescue Plan. This is something @SenatorBennet, @SenSherrodBrown, @raphaelwarnock and I fought hard to get included because of the historic, life-changing impact this will have on so many families: not only will 90% of American children benefit, this policy alone will effectively cut child poverty in half in this country. While we have so much to celebrate right now, we can’t stop here—we must make this expanded child tax credit permanent which is what I will be pushing for in the days ahead.

node.text: The failed war on drugs has really been a war on people—disproportionately people of color and low-income individuals. It’s long past time we end the prohibition on marijuana, expunge records, and restore justice to communities that have been beaten down by the unjust drug war. Today I joined Majority Leader @SenSchumer and @RonWyden to announce our plan to get this done.

More Americans have died from gun violence in my lifetime than in every single war in our nation's history. Somehow we don't think we can stop this—but we can.
 
Universal background checks.
Assault weapons ban.
Gun licensing.
 
That’s where it starts—let’s get it done.

node.text:
My childhood best friend died in the World Trade Center. I found his name on the memorial in Jersey City, Liberty Park and was overcome with emotion. 

He and I lost touch over the years, college and the struggles and striving of our twenties. 

News of his death just overwhelmed me. So many of us were already experiencing an obesity of grief; the enormity of the tragedy so traumatized. And then for me, this news.

I was transported back to his house; his amazing family; his loving parents that treated me like an adopted son; our crazy childhood games; him introducing me to rock classics; lemonade stands; games in the pool; playing with Star Wars action figures; his family teaching this little black boy how to make Irish soda bread and then declaring that I was now part Irish ...the memories just made me weep...and thank God for each one of them. 

And God his parents, sister, and other loved ones, their unimaginable agony. 

Thousands and thousands of people lost those they knew and loved on that day. Sadness has been seared into our collective souls. 

And yet I know I am who I am in part because of the invincible impact of the love that my friend lived in his tragically short life. 

My childhood knew such joy, such kindness, such nurturing and generous acts of grace. This was my childhood best friend and their family: in my most formative years, they loved me. 

Terrorists took his life but his love lives forever in the lives he touched. 

The love of all those sainted souls can not be erased or eliminated. It lives. 

Death can end a life; but it can never end our love.

I honor that formative friendship in my life by rededicating myself to loving - by doing my best to pour my life into that most noble of human pursuits: to love one another, courageously, relentlessly, unconditionally. 

May James Andrew O'Grady Rest In Peace; the legacy of his love lives on.

We have a collective moral mission, to reaffirm how we live in remembrance. 

Let us strive to show the same courage in our compassion; strength in our empathy; grit in generosity and invincibility in our love for one another as those did on that day, who died, who responded, who stood up when they tried to knock our nation down. 

Today is about reflection and ceremony... and it must also be about how we, the living, dedicate our lives.

node.text: Millions of American families are about to receive up to $3,600 per child thanks to the expanded child tax credit in the American Rescue Plan. This is something @SenatorBennet, @SenSherrodBrown, @raphaelwarnock and I fought hard to get included because of the historic, life-changing impact this will have on so many families: not only will 90% of American children benefit, this policy alone will effectively cut child poverty in half in this country. While we have so much to celebrate right now, we can’t stop here—we must make this expanded child tax credit permanent which is what I will be pushing for in the days ahead.

node.text:
In 2019, I had the chance to walk down Greenwood Street, visit the Vernon AME Church and meet with Black-owned business owners. It was one of the most meaningful and emotional days I can remember. 100 years ago in Greenwood, hundreds of Black Americans were killed, Black property and businesses destroyed, and churches burned in a targeted attack by a white mob. 

To truly heal, we need to tell that truth. Maya Angelou said, “There is no greater agony than bearing an untold story.” We must tell the story of the massacre that happened a century ago. We must tell the story of justice so long delayed and denied.

node.text:
Here is to that fierce love; the kind that gets you up in the morning and chases you to bed at night; the kind that feeds you first even when they are hungry; nurses you back to health even when they are sick; and always makes you feel special even when you fail, fall, falter or just feel flattened.  

Here is to that impossible love; the kind that is always there; even when unappreciated, unacknowledged, undervalued or unaware. Here's to the love that shows up again and again, at games and matches and plays and recitals; to graduations that took years to achieve and for art projects left to the last minute. Here's to the love that appears right on time with bedtime stories and bandaids, with delicious snacks and invaluable kernels of wisdom. 

Here is to my mother and yours. Here's to Moms of biology and Moms of spirit. Here's to Moms who save children and Moms who serve neighborhoods and communities. Here's to the Moms who adopt, who step in, and step up. Here's to Moms who expand their hearts and their homes and make children without  theirs within their hearts. 

Moms, here is to every tear you dried and every one you have cried; here is to every hurt you healed and every wound you still carry. And here is to all those days you worked when you were so, so weary and loved us unconditionally even amidst a nation that doesn't value all Moms - beyond words or just a day - with meaningful paid family leave, adequate postpartum health care, or high quality affordable child care. 

Thank you Mom - Carolyn Booker. I love you. 

And thank you ALL Moms I love you too and I rejoice in you today and every day.

(Picture of my brother Cary and me with my mom, my real life Wonder Woman.)

May The Fourth.... Happy Star Wars Day. 

I just turned 8 years old when the original Star Wars came out. It was a movie that changed me. It inspired me; it made me believe in the power of underdogs in a righteous cause; it affirmed to me the limitless strength of committed friendships, and expanded my sense of the magic and mystery of the universe. And yes, The Force spoke to my burgeoning sense of faith and the connectedness of all things. 

May The Force Be With You... and May The Force always be Grace, Empathy, Kindness and Relentless Love. 

Lightsaber was a gift from my staff. 

Photo Credit to @rosariodawson, the only truly trained Jedi I know, who caught me post morning work out.
